                <!-- SEO Content Area -->
                <article class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md mt-8 prose">
                    <h2>Data Source and Methodology</h2>
                    <p><strong>Authoritative Source:</strong> Internal Revenue Service (IRS), Section 1031 of the Internal Revenue Code, "Like-Kind Exchanges - Real Estate Tax Tips".
                    <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/like-kind-exchanges-real-estate-tax-tips" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">IRS Official Guidance</a></p>
                    <p>All calculations are strictly based on IRS Section 1031 regulations. This calculator implements standard capital gains deferral formulas used by real estate professionals and tax advisors.</p>

                    <h2>The Formula Explained</h2>
                    <div class="formula-box">
                        <p><strong>Capital Gain:</strong> Current Property Value - (Purchase Price + Improvement Costs)</p>
                        <p><strong>Tax Deferred:</strong> Capital Gain × Tax Rate</p>
                        <p><strong>Adjusted Basis:</strong> Purchase Price + Improvement Costs</p>
                    </div>

                    <h2>Glossary of Variables</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Current Property Value:</strong> The current fair market value of the property you are selling</li>
                        <li><strong>Purchase Price:</strong> The original price paid when you acquired the property</li>
                        <li><strong>Improvement Costs:</strong> Capital improvements made to the property (renovations, additions, etc.)</li>
                        <li><strong>Tax Rate:</strong> Your applicable capital gains tax rate (Federal long-term capital gains rate)</li>
                        <li><strong>Adjusted Basis:</strong> Your total investment in the property (purchase price + improvements)</li>
                        <li><strong>Capital Gain:</strong> The profit from the sale before taxes</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h2>How It Works: A Step-by-Step Example</h2>
                    <p>Let's calculate tax deferral for a property sold for $500,000:</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Original Purchase Price:</strong> $300,000</li>
                        <li><strong>Improvement Costs:</strong> $50,000</li>
                        <li><strong>Adjusted Basis:</strong> $300,000 + $50,000 = $350,000</li>
                        <li><strong>Capital Gain:</strong> $500,000 - $350,000 = $150,000</li>
                        <li><strong>Tax Rate:</strong> 15%</li>
                        <li><strong>Tax Deferred:</strong> $150,000 × 0.15 = $22,500</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p>By completing a proper 1031 exchange, you can defer paying $22,500 in capital gains taxes and reinvest the full proceeds into a new property.</p>

                    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>What is a 1031 Exchange?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">A 1031 exchange, named after Section 1031 of the Internal Revenue Code, allows real estate investors to defer capital gains taxes on the sale of a property by reinvesting the proceeds into a "like-kind" replacement property.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>Who qualifies for a 1031 Exchange?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Any taxpayer that owns real property held for investment or business purposes can qualify. Personal residences do not qualify.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>What are the time limits for a 1031 Exchange?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">You must identify replacement property within 45 days of selling your original property, and you must complete the purchase within 180 days of the sale.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>Can I use a 1031 Exchange for my primary residence?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">No, 1031 exchanges only apply to investment or business properties. For primary residences, consider the Section 121 exclusion instead.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>What happens if I don't find a replacement property in time?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">If you fail to meet either the 45-day or 180-day deadline, the exchange fails, and you will owe capital gains taxes on the sale in that tax year.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>Do I need to use a Qualified Intermediary?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Yes, IRS regulations require you to use a Qualified Intermediary (QI) to facilitate the exchange. You cannot receive the sale proceeds directly.</p>
                    </details>

                    <div class="mt-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg border border-gray-200">
